items.content: Business and retail packages will be halted from today after US President Donald Trump imposed tariffs on low-value parcels.

items.title: Australia Post suspends deliveries to the US
items.standfirst: The company announced the measures were in response to the changes in import rules and tariffs imposed by Donald Trump.
items.content: Australia Post has announced it will suspend parcel deliveries to the United States and Puerto Rico until further notice.In a statement released this morning, the company announced the measures had been taken in response to the changes in import rules and tariffs imposed by US President Donald Trump.This includes the suspension of the De Minimis exemption for inbound goods below $US800 ($1233) and requiring the pre-payment of tariffs before an item's arrival in the US.READ MORE: 'Not deserving of the court's mercy': Life in jail awaits Erin PattersonThe temporary suspension will impact Business Contract, MyPost Business and Retail customers sending goods through the postal network.Postal goods sent to the US, including its territory Puerto Rico, logged on or after August 26 will not be accepted, however gifts under $US100, letters and documents will still be able to be sent.They claim it is in line with the actions of many other postal networks around the world.READ MORE: Four journalists killed in Israeli strike on Gaza hospital"We are disappointed we have had to take this action, however, due to the complex and rapidly evolving situation, a temporary partial suspension has been necessary to allow us to develop and implement a workable solution for our customers," Australia Post executive general manager Gary Starr said."Guidance from CBP (US Customs and Border Protection) has only recently been issued and, like more than 190 other postal providers, we've been working at pace to find a solution."Australia Post say they are working with Zonos, an authorised third-party provider to find a solution that will allow the suspended services to resume."Australia Post continues to work with US and Australian authorities and international postal partners to resume postal service to the US as a priority," Starr said.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. items.title: Two-year-old boy on life support in hospital after being hit by car
items.standfirst: The toddler was with his father riding on a balance bike at a pedestrian crossing when a white van struck him, police said.
items.content: The toddler was with his father riding on a balance bike at a pedestrian crossing when a white van struck him, police said.

items.title: Toddler fighting for life after being hit by van in Melbourne
items.standfirst: T he child was crossing a pedestrian crossing on a balance bike when they were hit overnight.
items.content: A toddler is fighting for their life after they were hit by a van in Melbourne's south-east overnight.It's understood a white van was travelling west on Thames Promenade in Chelsea Heights, near the intersection of Mulkarra Drive, when it struck the toddler at about 9.10pm.The child was on a small balance bike using the pedestrian crossing, accompanied by a man walking with them.READ MORE: Dangerous inmate only cell contact for mushroom killer An off-duty police officer who was passing stopped to provide first aid, before emergency services arrived.The child was taken to hospital with serious injuries and remains in a critical condition.The man with the toddler was not injured.READ MORE: WA petrol station erupts in fireball A 29-year-old Clyde man, who was driving the van, was arrested and interviewed but has been released pending further enquiries.The investigation into the crash continues.Any witnesses or anybody with dashcam footage, CCTV or other information, is urged to contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000 or online.
